SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1105
By Bailey
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of John Richard Fox of
Gainesboro.
WHEREAS, the members of this General Assembly were greatly saddened to learn of
the passing of John Richard Fox of Gainesboro; and
WHEREAS, John Fox was an exemplary public servant and consummate professional
who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for his fellow citizens in numerous
capacities; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Fox was born on April 12, 1939, in Gainesboro to Robert M. and Elsie
Fox; and
WHEREAS, John Fox began his career as a teacher at Jackson County High School
and later served in administration as supervisor of instruction and superintendent of schools;
and
WHEREAS, Mr. Fox also served as mayor of Gainesboro and president of the Jackson
County Historical Society; he was deeply passionate about Jackson County history, working
diligently to preserve the Robert M. Fox School building and the Jackson County Historical
Museum; and
WHEREAS, throughout his life, John Fox devoted himself to the people of Jackson
County, leaving a lasting impact on countless students, families, and community members, and
he gave back to local athletics by serving as a referee and scout for the Blue Devils; and
WHEREAS, a man of deep faith, Mr. Fox was a lifetime member of the Gainesboro
Church of Christ, where he served as a treasurer, Bible school teacher, preacher, and elder;
and
SJR1105
017486
- 1 -

WHEREAS, John Fox's favorite pastimes included going to University of Tennessee
football games, golfing, relaxing with a cigar, and eating good meals with friends and
colleagues; and
WHEREAS, John Fox will be remembered for his steady presence, his leadership, and
his unwavering dedication to his family and community; and
WHEREAS, Mr. Fox is survived by his children, Dodd (Susan) Galbreath, Dene (Trisha)
Galbreath, Melyn (Mark) Galbreath, and Nan (Darian) Coons; grandchildren, Ryan Galbreath
(fiancée Kadie), Nicholas (Gracie) Galbreath, Braden (Brynn) Galbreath, Ailey Galbreath,
Andersen Negley, Georgia Coons, and Duel Coons; and a host of extended family and friends;
and
WHEREAS, in addition to his parents, he was preceded in death by his brother, Ted
Fox, and his beloved wife, Helen Fox; and
WHEREAS, John Fox leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public
life, compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all his chosen
endeavors; and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly should remember the
bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, THE HOUSE OF
REPRESENTATIVES CONCURRING, that we honor the memory of John Richard Fox,
reflecting fondly upon his impeccable character and his stalwart commitment to living the
examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we extend our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family of Mr. Fox.
- 2 - 017486

BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy and upon proper request made to
the appropriate clerk, the language appearing immediately following the State seal appear
without House or Senate designation.
